Background

This HW is based on Hans Rosling talks New Insights on Poverty and The Best Stats Youve Ever Seen.

The assignment uses data to answer specific question about global health and economics. The data contradicts commonly held preconceived notions. For example, Hans Rosling starts his talk by asking: (paraphrased) for each of the six pairs of countries below, which country do you think had the highest child mortality in 2015?

  1. Sri Lanka or Turkey
  2. Poland or South Korea
  3. Malaysia or Russia
  4. Pakistan or Vietnam
  5. Thailand or South Africa

Most people get them wrong. Why is this? In part it is due to our preconceived notion that the world is divided into two groups: the Western world versus the third world, characterized by long life,small family and short life, large family respectively. In this homework we will use data visualization to gain insights on this topic.

b = life_expectancy %>%
  gather(country, life_expectancy)
c = fertility %>%
  gather(country, fertility)

fixpopulation <- function(x,i){
  y <- strsplit(as.character(x[,i]),",")
  ret <- sapply(y, function(z){
    if(length(z)>=4){as.numeric(z[1])*1000000000 + as.numeric(z[2])*1000000 + as.numeric(z[3])*1000 + as.numeric(z[4])}
    else if(length(z)>=3){as.numeric(z[1])*1000000 + as.numeric(z[2])*1000 + as.numeric(z[3])}
    else if(length(z)>=2){as.numeric(z[1])*1000 + as.numeric(z[2])}
    else{as.numeric(z[1])}
  })
  return(ret)
}

d = as.data.frame(matrix(0,nrow(population),ncol(population)))
for (j in 2:ncol(population)){
  d[,j] = fixpopulation(population,j)
  population[,j]=d[,j]
}

e = population %>%
  gather(country, population)

f = total_gdp %>%
  gather(country, total_gdp)

names(b)[2] = "year"
names(c)[2] = "year"
names(e)[2] = "year"
names(f)[2] = "year"

Problem 3

To examine if in fact there was a long-life-in-a-small-family and short-life-in-a-large-family dichotomy, we will visualize the average number of children per family (fertility) and the life expectancy for each country.

Problem 3.1

Use ggplot2 to create a plot of life expectancy versus fertiltiy for 1962 for Africa, Asia, Europe, and the Americas. Use color to denote continent and point size to denote population size:

library(ggplot2)
cbbPalette <- c("#000000", "#E69F00", "#56B4E9", "#009E73", "#F0E442", "#D55E00", "#0072B2", "#CC79A7")

p <- ggplot(filter(dat1, year == 1962 & continent != "Oceania"),aes(x = fertility, y = life_expectancy))
p + geom_point(aes(color = continent, size = population))+ 
    scale_size(range = c(1,18)) +theme(text = element_text(size=14),axis.text.x = element_text(size =12), axis.text.y = element_text(size =12),legend.text=element_text(size=12))+ggtitle("Life Expectancy vs. Fertility 1962")+labs(x = "Fertility", y = "Life Expectancy")+scale_colour_manual(values=cbbPalette)

Do you see a dichotomy? Explain.

Yes. Most countries in Asia and Africa had higher fertility and lower life expectancy while those in Europe had lower fertility and higher life expectancy in 1962. Countries in Americas were spread in between the two extremes. Since this is a cross-sectional data, its hard to tell if life expectancy affected fertility or the other way around. Possible explanations can be that African and Asian countries had lower life expectancy (which can due to higher children mortality/lower children survival, etc) so that was the reason why they want to have more children to make sure some of the descendants can live longer than the low threshold.

dat1 = dat1 %>%
  mutate(OECD = FALSE) %>%
  mutate(OPEC = FALSE) %>%
  mutate(member = as.character(continent))
for (i in 1:length(dat1$country)){
  if (dat1$country[i] %in% oecd){
    dat1$OECD[i] <- TRUE
    dat1$member[i] <- "OECD"
  }
  else if (dat1$country[i] %in% opec){
    dat1$OPEC[i] <- TRUE
    dat1$member[i] <- "OPEC"
  }
  else if (dat1$continent[i] %in% c("Europe","Oceania"))
    dat1$member[i] <- "Others"
}

How would you describe the dichotomy?

OECD countries are at the top left of this plot (less fertility and higher life expectancy) while the OPEC countries are around the bottom right of this plot (higher fertility and less life expectancy). It seems to me that developed countries have higher life expectancy and less fertility rate compared to other countries (especially developing countries in Africa and Asia). For OPEC countries, although they were at the bottom right corner, they had slightly higher life expectancy and less fertility rates compared to none-OPEC Asian/African countries. This may give us some hints that economic development is related to life expectancy and fertility rates (OPEC countries have oil and therefore may have higher GDP per capita; OPEC countries were observed to have higher life expectancy and lower fertility rates compared to other developing countries in Africa and Asia).

I noticed some OECD countries in the graph located in the middle and even bottom right of the graph so I filtered them out. They are Chile, Mexico and Turkey, and all three of them are still developing countries in 2015. Chile and Turkey were not OECD countries yet while Turkey has enrolled since 1961.

Also, more and more people have got chance to expose to knowledge of birth control and age of first marriage has also increased gradually among several countries.

Problem 4.1

Lets compare France and its former colony Tunisia. Make a plot of fertility versus year with color denoting the country. Do the same for life expecancy. How would you compare Tunisias improvement compared to Frances in the past 60 years? Hint: use geom_line

p <- ggplot(filter(dat1, country == "France" | country == "Tunisia"), aes(x = as.numeric(year), y = fertility,group = country))+ geom_line(aes(color = country),size = 1.5)
p+scale_x_continuous("year",limits = c(1955, 2015))+theme(text = element_text(size=14),axis.text.x = element_text(size =12), axis.text.y = element_text(size =12),legend.text=element_text(size=12))+ggtitle("Fertility over time")+labs(y = "Fertility")+scale_colour_manual(values=cbbPalette)

p <- ggplot(filter(dat1, country == "France" | country == "Tunisia"), aes(x = as.numeric(year), y = life_expectancy,group = country))+ geom_line(aes(color = country),size = 1.5)
p+scale_x_continuous("year",limits = c(1955, 2015))+theme(text=element_text(size=14),axis.text.x = element_text(size =12), axis.text.y = element_text(size=12),legend.text=element_text(size=12))+ggtitle("Life expectance over time")+labs(y = "Life Expectancy")+scale_colour_manual(values=cbbPalette)

The fertility of Tunisia decreased (a lot) from 6+ to 2 during the past 60 years while that of france decreased but not that much. The Life expectance of Tunisia increased by 1.5 fold (20+ years) during the past 60 years and that of France increased by 1.2 fold (10+ years) during the same period. Tunisia has improved more in terms of the abosolute change of increasing life expectancy and decreasing fertility rate.

Problem 5

We are now going to examine GDP per capita per day.

Problem 5.1

Create a smooth density estimate of the distribution of GDP per capita per day across countries in 1970. Include OECD, OPEC, Asia, Africa, and the Americas in the computation. When doing this we want to weigh countries with larger populations more. We can do this using the weight" argument in geom_density.

dat1 <- mutate(dat1, gdp_capita_d = total_gdp/population/365)
p <- ggplot(filter(dat1, year == 1970 & (continent%in%c("Asia","Africa","Americas") | member%in%c("OECD","OPEC")) ), aes(gdp_capita_d))
p+ geom_density(aes(weight=population, fill = "orange"))+theme(text = element_text(size=14),axis.text.x = element_text(size =12), axis.text.y = element_text(size =12),legend.text=element_text(size=12))+ggtitle("GDP per capita per day 1970")+labs(x = "GDP per capita per day")+ guides(fill=FALSE)

Problem 5.2

Now do the same but show each of the five groups separately.

# For countries in Americas, Asia and Africa, if they are in either OECD or OPEC, I categorize them as OECD or OPEC countries to avoid double counting in multiple graphs.

p <- ggplot(filter(dat1, year == 1970 & (member%in%c("OECD","OPEC","Americas","Asia","Africa"))), aes(gdp_capita_d))
p+ geom_density(aes(weight=population),fill = "orange")+facet_grid(member~.)+theme(text = element_text(size=14),axis.text.x = element_text(size =12), axis.text.y = element_text(size =12),legend.text=element_text(size=12))+ggtitle("GDP per capita per day 1970")+labs(x = "GDP per capita per day")+ guides(fill=FALSE) + scale_y_sqrt()

Problem 5.3

Visualize these densities for several years. Show a couple of of them. Summarize how the distribution has changed through the years.

p <- ggplot(filter(dat1, year%in% seq(1970,2010,10) & (member%in%c("OECD","OPEC","Americas","Asia","Africa"))), aes(gdp_capita_d))
p+ geom_density(aes(weight=population, fill = factor(year)))+facet_wrap(c("member","year"),nrow = 5)+theme(text = element_text(size=14),axis.text.x = element_text(size =12), axis.text.y = element_text(size =12),legend.text=element_text(size=12))+ggtitle("GDP per capita per day")+labs(x = "GDP per capita per day")+ guides(fill=FALSE) + scale_y_sqrt()

The variation of GDP per capita per day among OECD countries has increased more than other category of countries over the past 50 years, meaning that the economy of some OECD countries might have been left behind that of other OECD countries. Overall, OECD countries still have GDP per capita way greater than other parts of the world.
